>>29460235
>2. If they were even remotely a good gauge of innate intelligence potential, why would retaking them have a massive improvement in score?
I don't want to go rummaging for studies right now, but I will say this:

A person who scores average on an IQ test may be able to improve their scores on THAT specific test, but when they take a different test with items they haven't encountered before, their score tends to drops right back down to average.

>4. I did outperform you on verbal, so at least I have that going for me

Verbal intelligence tends to have the highest "g-loading". That is to say it has the highest correlation with other aspects of intelligence. Verbal intelligence is also extremely resilient to practice. Both these facts may seem counterintuitive, but consider that most people have been exposed to their native language their entire life, so they've effectively hit a performance plateau by adulthood. Also, verbal intelligence isn't simply a test of knowledge; if you don't know the definition of a word, you can break down its components and take a guess at the etymology and therefore the meaning. So, scoring well on the verbal subsection is something you can be proud of

sampling voices from tv can still b really cool. it is an artistic limitation you have to work around but you can say a lot.

you can imply a lot w what you sample from too. there's a really cool extra dimension to it.

you could also sample other musicians. or find a single singer/speaker with a huge catalogue of recordings and stitch just them into vocal lines.

you could use an ai voice

you could use a talkbox to apply your own voice formant to a musical note

there's a lotta options I think it depends if you have a vision for a way to use those limitations artistically

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>29462170
5mg (NOT 5ml, don't be stupid) every 7 days should be enough. But you should check your levels right before your next injection.
Iirc, your lowest levels (the ones before your next injection) should be around 250-300 so your T is adequately suppressed. However, it may not be enough, so you should check your T too and increase your dose slightly to see if it works. I'm assuming you'll do mono and stop taking cypro.
Also, there's good chance you'll think you're masculinizing even if your T levels are fine. That happens probably because the little T you have was being blocked by your cypro. If you don't take it anymore, the fem T you have will be free to act, just like it happens with cis women.
You're supposed to inject it into a muscle, either your vastus lateralis or your glutes. Just search on youtube how to inject into those. I think you can inject it subcutaneously too, and it would make it last longer because subq allows you to use insulin syringes which have zero dead space. I injected using normal luer slip syringes and they would was a significant amount of E in the dead space, which made my vial last a few months less than it could theoretically last. However, there's not much research into injecting hormones subq, so it would be safer to inject it into the muscle.

>>29461859
>does marching around with signs and screaming even do anything?
Somewhat.
I think what people get mixed up is that they presume every action you do is to convince the people outside the action to support your cause.
But a lot of actions are actually targeted at the people DOING the action and escalating their level of commitment.
You've definitely got a core of die-hards, for which no amount of additional actions will increase their level of commitment (but sometimes you still need regular interaction in order to maintain their interest and belief the cause is accomplishing something).
But then you've got a group of people who feel at least enough engagement to the issue to show up to a march. But that engagement might be a temporary thing. e.g. there's a lot of news about statements by a certain controversial politician, but once the media cycle moves onto another topic, that group's engagement might disappear or be forgotten. Participating in an event is a way to increase that engagement to another level. Now they aren't just "inclined to support" but have made a public commitment of support. They remember being at the march, the people they talked to (or at least were surrounded by), the speakers they listened to (you remembered to have public speakers, right organizers?) and now have a personal social connection to the group.
And then you've got a group of people who only showed up because a friend/partner/coworker asked them to go. So they're participating, but they may not have engagement with the cause going into things. The march is an opportunity to escalate them to a supporter.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>29462108
This. It reminds them that there are actually quite a few of us.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>29462190
(too long)
Also, depending on the level of organizing sophistication, there's also a whole layer of data collection benefits from having an event. You've got people who sign up for email reminders or Facebook events or whatever, so you've got new contact information you can reach out to later. You've also collected info on which supporters showed up (even just from recognizing their faces in person), so you know which supporters to prioritize targeting in the future.
This is why you may be getting so many spam emails with retard-level engagement like "please retweet!" It's shit for impact, but it's about the data collection aspect.
At least with a march you have a plausible claim you're doing something, but it is a higher level of commitment than some people are willing to make. So you get more "please retweet!" trash working up to it.

So should you show up to the march? I dunno, your choice frens. But I've literally read the scientific papers to back up this shit: organizing theory works overall, and we just argue about the exact statistical values of different coefficients in different times & places. So maybe have some faith that there are professionals out there doing this work.

>If you use copyrighted material to create a product that you pass off as your own, especially for money, you can get in trouble.
This happens all the time. It's the basis of every creative work. Everyone is consciously or unconsciously copying what others have done before. We just learn to mask it by copying 10% from 10 different people and then we get to declare it's "ours".

>AI companies go out on their own to obtain the material in question even if they're aimlessly scraping. It's still they're doing. Negligence on their behalf.
Yeah if they were caught with all those pictures on a company hard drive and it was determined illegal to use copyrighted pictures in neural network training then I guess they would be pretty fucked. It's not a crime right now though.

>it's irrelevant because copyright law doesn't care what ideas you have. Unless of course it's your intellectual property and you can sue over it.
The law on copyright broadly is that there needs to be substantial similarity in order to incriminate someone of breaching copyright. Which generally means it's just a complete copy of the original with minimal changes if any. If the work in question is properly transformative then it's usually completely fine. This is why parodies can be made and sold as their own IP even while the original's creators complain about it.

Helping friends Edition
previous: >>29406341

Goal of the thread: Work on one skill you wish to be better at. It can be as simple as reading a small paragraph of a text book on the subject.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

What I mean by "plan, measure, adjust" is that you should never expect the initial schedule to be realistic. You can always do more than you planned: It just feels better to over perform on a day rather than under perform, so a conservative estimate is better. Once you planed, you actually stick to with with some flexibility and see whether you find yourself consistently doing more than planned. Also account for rest and sick days, your 3 reserve days are an excellent idea.

Without being hard on yourself, try to think through what you might be doing which is a cause...

This is all like, nonverbal communication type stuff, so it sounds cringe to say out loud because it seems like I'm referring to nonviolent communication, but I'm not.
